value.0: A dirty job, but someone has to do it.

Value.value: Ugh... I don't recommend going down there. Whole place is flooded and full of... uh... Waste.

value.0: A dirty job, but someone has to do it.

Value.value: Why do we have to stay down here...? Ugh!

value.0: Malcer looks around uneasily, as if expecting something to come out of the shadows around him.

Value.value: Hey, you. Ya goin' into this mess down 'ere?
I could use some help, if ya've got time. See, me ruddy employees don't wanna come t'work. Had some of 'em go missin' so it makes sense...
Get in 'ere and have a look 'round, maybe find out what got our lads, and I got some coin for ya. Maybe somethin' else if I find somethin' else.
If ya can help me find what's what, maybe the boss'll give us some hazard pay.
Hells, that's dangerous! You said it was an ooze? Ochre jelly? What? I'll take this sample to the boss. Cheers. And here's the reward I promised. I did find somethin' else, after all.
'Eyyy, good ta see ya again. If yer lookin' for more work, the farmers in Frontier's Rest have been havin' goblin troubles, I heard.
Ya find what's been nabbin' me boys yet? Eh.

Light and dust filters down from service holes in the floor of the arena looming somewhere above. The blood of combatants streaks down the walls from where it has dripped time and time again, mingling with the detris on the ground that has been swept through when the arena is being restored to neat presentation.

The air is humid and fetid down here, ripe with the stench of offal, brine, and other unpleasant smells. The ground below the platform under a couple fingers of bay water - and  up to several feet at high tide - that flows slowly westward. Nearly everything is coated in some kind of moisture or slime, and the only light is that which filters down from the grates in the street far above, or from the few guttering torches provided.
The smell of sewage is particularly pungent here. All of the water and refuse from other regions of the sewers is channeled by a gradual, descending slope to lead to this one tunnel.

Approaching the stairs, an occasional draft clears the air of foulness and flies, and even the scent of swamp trickling in is a welcome change from the reek of sewage trapped in the tunnels.

Coming down from the stairs is a less enjoyable experience as the air is humid and fetid down here, ripe with the stench of offal, brine, and other unpleasant smells. The floor of the tunnel is slick with bay water that flows slowly soouthwestward. Nearly everything is coated in some kind of moisture or slime, and the only light is that which filters down from the grates in the street far above, or from the few guttering torches provided.
